{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_jaguar_ver01/data/sn86088651/00202191137/1913101401/0341.xml":{"full_text":"Cooper C7pe\n\"QUALITY GROCERS\"\nWe are exclusive agents for the FAMOUS\nWhite Eagle Flour\nmade by the J. C. Lysles Milling Company.\nIf you want the best millers can produce,\norder WHITE EAGLE- ItB the\nstandard- Every sack guaranteed\nPhones 32-386\nTHE BRYAN DAILY EAGLE\nAND PILOT.\npbllhd Every Day Excpt Sunday\ny THE EAGLE PRINTING CO.\nMEMBER OP ASSOCIATED PRESS\ni. J. BUCHANAN Editor\nU. B. WALLACE .Manager\nEntered as aeoond-class matter April\nit, ltie, at the poatofflce at Bryan,\nfoxaa, under the Act of March 8, 1879.\nv RaUe of Subscription:\nOat Month.\n.40\n1.00\n4.00\nram Months.\nDb Tear.\nAvertUing rates on applicaUon. 1\nSubscribers will confer a favor on\nko management hy telephoning the\ndee promptly when carrier fall to\nOliver the paper, or when change of\nresidence occur.\nKOTICE TO ADVERTISERS AND\nSUBSCRIBERS\nHereafter all copy for display adver\ntisements will have to reach our office\nby 10 a. m. in order to appear In The\nEagle on that day. Owing to the short\nwinter day, and in order to give the\nbeet possible service to subscriber\nand advertiser alike, this arrangement\n-win be strictly adhered to. Parties\nnot receiving their paper by 6 p. m.\nwill please notify the office. Telephone\nNo. 38. Local and want ads must be\nbrought or telephoned in not later\nthan 2 p. m.\nWILL CONE BE A CANDIDATE?\nA few days ago Houston was hon\nored by a visit from the Hon. Cone\nJohnson of Tyler. Physically Mr.\nJohnson seemed in splendid trim, but\nwhether or not he Is in training for\nnext year's political handicap, we did\nnot learn.- When asked by a State's\nTopic representative, in the lobby of\nthe Rice Hotel, how he regarded the\npolitical atmosphere, he said he\nthought It a little murky.\" Further\nthan this he did not express himself\npolitically; and when someone suggest\ned that \"it was no longer a question\nof the biggest man for State office, but\nrather the littlest,\" be did nothing\nmore than smile and said he was \"go\ning up on the roof, where it was al\nways cool and the atmosphere fine.\"\n(Of course he had reference to the\nRice Hotel's Roof Garden.) While in\nAustin recently Mr. Johnson expressed\nhimself as favorable to a proposition\nwhich he thinks would be a happy so\nlution of prohibition. His propo\nsition, according to the Ballanger Led\nger, is \"to draft a State-wide prohibi\ntion amendment that would give the\npeople in each county the right to vote\nfor the sale of beer and light wines\nwithin its confines, In the event the\nprohibition amendment was adopted,\nand cut out what he calls 'real booze.'\nIn other words, It would be a vote to\ncut booze out of Texas and then let\nthe voters in each county say whether\nbeer Bhould be sold In the county,\"\nThe Ledger then adds: \"He has some\nfollowers who have advocated such a\nlaw, and there are many people who\nsee no evil in beer, but are opposed to\nwhiskey. It Is nothing more than what\none might call a compromise.\" Mr.\nJohnson's proposition might prove a\nsolution of the question, but why is it\nnecessary to first commit the State to\nStatewide prohibition before putting\nit In effect? While Mr. Johnson had\nthe appearance of a man who wouldn't\nmind a little political scrap, yet he\ndidn't so much a intimate that he\nwould be a candidate for State office\nnext year, although he did express\nhimself a being strongly in favor of\nnominating \"a good, man for Gover\nnor.\" State Topic.\nThree Wagons\nCol. Roosevelt's sister, Mrs. Douglas\nRobinson, is on the stump in New Jer\nsey speaking for the Progressives In\nthe gubernatorial campaign. She is\nsaid to be a good speaker. Tyler Courier-Times.\nAh, ha! In the above we find the\nexplanation as to how it were pos\nsible for the Colonel to take a lay-off\nand go gunning to the jungles of\nSouth America. He leaves a substi\ntute who fills the bill.\nThe transportation agencies, the\nmanufacturers, the wholesalers, the\nJobbers, the retailers and the various\nother agencies that handle and fatten\noff the products of the farmers from\nthe time they leave the farm until\nthey get back to him in the finished\nproduct, are the things that keep his\nnose to the grind-stone, and always\nwill, tariff or no tariff, until some of\nthem are eliminated.\nWoman's talk that she can't go be\ncause she has nothing to wear is no\nlonger a reasonable excuse for remain\ning away. The styles have changed.\nTyler Courier-Times.\nPoor Col. Green, you have our heart\nfelt sympathy in the storm of woman's\nfury that Is sure to overtake you\n\"For that, for that they'll get thy fer-\nrln\nIn bell they'll roast thee like a herrln'.\"\nIt has been shouted from the house\ntops that the Republican protective\ntariff was the mother of the trusts\nand made it possible for them to live.\nThe Democratic revised tariff has now\nbeen in force nearly two weeks, and\nthough we have our ear glued to the\n-ground, we have not yet heard the fun\neral announcement of any of the\ntrusts.\nThe court house square with its un\neven surface, its weeds and uncut\ngrass. Is about as uninviting a spot\nas could be found anywhere. It should\nbe the \"beauty-spot\" of the county,\nand the people would be glad to see a\nI little of the tax money go for that pur\npose.\nThe Federal game laws, signed by\nPresident Wilson on October 1, are\nnow in effect The duck season under\ni this law is from November 1 to Feb\nruary 1, and it Is therefore a violation\nof the Federal game law to shoot\nducks until November 1.\nThere is some talk of another special\nsession of the Legislature to be con-\nvened early next year. The Lord de\nj liver us! They make it worse every\nI time, and we had better let it go as\nit is.\nThe powers that be should adopt fa\npositive policy for Bryan on weed cut\nting and sanitation. We have been\nliving negatively long enough.\nThe trouble with Governor Sulzer\nseems to be that he did not have his\n\"quarrel Just,\" and was therefore not\n\"thrice armed.\"\nA one-cylinder individual trying to\nrun a six-cylinder business, Is a pow\nerful aid to the high cost of living.\nPOINTED PARAGRAPHS\nMany a humble lover makes a boss\nhusband.\nHow easy for a weak man to break\na promise!\nOne way to make a sure thing doubt\nful is to bet on it\nI The best cantaloupe Is as hard to se\nlect as the best automobile.\nOccasionally a commercial drum\nmer prevents his modesty from crowd\ning to the front.\nSome men refuse to quarrel with\ntheir wives because it costs them too\nmuch to make up.\nA man never has much to fear from\na woman who is fat enough to shako\nwhen she laughs.\nTHE BRYAN\nTHE OLD FARM AND THT NEW.\nAbout six years ago, in company\nwith a friend who was In quest of land,\n1 walked over a Piedmont farm. The\nway to the place led up out of a much\nfilled ravine, then on up an enlarged\ngullcy that served as the road to the\nhouse. Thorns and blackberry bushes\nplucked at our hats as we passed\nalong and through the little open\nspaces between the field pines, the\nbroomstraw was trying to hide' the\ngalled spots.\nFurther on, the brush-grown garden\nspot with its dilapidated fence, spoiled\nthe natural beauty of the home\ngrounds lovely yet In spite of the\nunpainted house with Its broken doors\nand windows.\nThe scale and grubs were holding\nhigh carnival in the old family or\nchard, and as we passed on over tha\nfarm everything spoke all too strongly\nof the poverty that follows In the wake\nof soil robbing. The little patches of\ntobbacco only tended to emphasize the\nhopelessness of the decay that every\nwhere abounded.\nA few days ago, with another friend\nI again visited this place which for\nabout three years now has been re\nceiving treatment from a man who\nloves the soil and who realize the re\nsponsibility that goes with its hand\nling. We drove along a carefully\ngraded road that dipped gradually to\nthe modest bridge, spanning the turb\nulent little creek. A five-foot woven\nwire fence, guarded a pretty field of\nclover and herdsgrass from the care\nless trespassers. Trotting rapidly\nalong the smooth road our rig passed\na fine large field of tobacco, then more\nfields of clover and grass, and finally\nmy friend exclaimed, \"What a pretty\nhome?\"\nAnd indeed it Is a pretty home,\nmodest and unpretentious, but com\npelling, as it stands there in its fresh\nness, surrounded by the beautiful oaks\nand grand cherry trees, flanked by the\nwell-kept garden, and backed by the\nbeauty of \"the everlasting hills.\" Good\ncows grazed In the lespedeza pasture\nat the rear and to the right fine stacks\nof hay stood as sentinels, proclaiming\nthe return of prosperity that surely\nfollows in the wake of the grass and\nclover that with their million of fib\nrous root bind the soil particles to\ngether and scotch for the farmer who\nIs bent on raising the soil out of the\nslough of despair Into which reckless\nsoil robbing has reduced It\nAs we drove on more fields of clover\nand herdsgrass came Into view, then\na goodly field of corn, and another to\nbacco. A sparkling spring stream was\ncrossed and flanking it on either side\nwas another modern pasture; while\non the opposite slope, where six years\nago rose tier on tier of gullies and\nrock-infested pine patches, the hands\nof this good farmer and his son had\nwrought a marvelous change. Not a\ngully, not a pine, was to be seen but\na great slopping beautiful meadow\nsmiled upon and kissed by the setting\nsun.\n''Ah yes.\" you say, \"the work vn-\ndoubtedly of a man of wealth.\" Not a\nbit of it The work rather of a man\nwith a stourt heart with a love for\nthe soil, and a realizing sense of the\ntruth, that a rich soil means, even\ntually, a rich people; while a poor soil\nalways spells poverty to the husband\nman. A. L. French, In The Progres\nsive Farmer.\nDON'T KEEP THE CHILDREN OUT\nOF SCHOOL TO PICK COTTON.\ni\nAny man can easily prepare and\nplant more land in cotton than he\ncan pick; and without the women and\nchildren to help him pick it the acre\nage in that plant would necessarily\nhave to be greatly reduced. But when\nwe keep the children out of school to\nhelp save the cotton crop we are com\nmitting a double crime against them.\nPA\nTO-DAY From 4:00 to 11 P. M.\nA GREAT TWO-REEL FEATURE WITH THAT\nPEERLESS ACTOR, WILLIAM SHAY\n1. Robespiere (Parti) Extra Attraction Imp\nA story of the French Revolution. Don't miss It The cos\ntume are correct\nI 2. Robespiere (Part 2) Exciting Irftp Feature\nSome fine view of the French prison, a thl was really\ntaken in France.\n3. Robespiere (Part 3) Ceo. Holliss' Masterpiece\nFeaturing such star William Shay, Jane Fearnley,\nW. E. Welch, and Grace Huntley. 1\n4. None Can Do More (Fine War Drama) Rex\nAn unusual war picture of the struggle between North\nand South,\n\"Robespiere,\" a Masterpiece in Three Reels Today,\nDon't Miss It. It's Great. Take a Tip from Me.\n4 REELS EACH DAY\nWILLIAM SHAY TONIGHT!\nTHE PALACE\nWE LEAD. OTHERS FOLLOW\nVWMWMMWWMMWMWWVMVWMWWWWWWWVWVWNAWMVMMAMAAAAAAAMAAAAAAAAAAAAMM\nDARY EAGLE\ni7ZS I I U f\nfesfrtgfal Rut kluAcr Mm\nYoung men are coming\nto us for clothes because\nthey find that our new.de\nsigns in Hart Schaffner\nMarx clothes are especially\nsmart; many new features\nhere that you won't find\nanywhere else.\nSuits and Overcoats $18 up\nSpecial values at $25.\nA. M.\nWaldrop\nCo.\nThe Store for Values in\nMen's Wear\nNot only are we rendering the soil\npoorer, but at the same time we are\ndepriving them of the opportunity of\nsecuring that education which will\nbe doubly necessary to them in order\nthat they may make a living from the\nsoils that we have already exhausted.\nThe fields of our beautiful Southland\nare today filled, with children, each\none bending his little back and, work\ning his little hands and brains to help\ndestroy and reduce his own chancos\nof malting the living that we should\nassure him when he grow to man'\nestate. Better have less cotton and\nlet those little backs grV straight\nand strong in play and have those\neyes and those brains employed in the\nschoolhouse that, i now empty.\nWe' owe It to those children that we\nshall leave them, strong bodies and\nhands and minds trained and fitted\nto the best of our ability to fight life's\nbattle. With these things we can rest\nassured that they will win for them\nselves a good living; while if we de\nprive them of the opportunity of se\ncuring these things, we ran rest-assured\nthat the home and the farm\nwill only be their.' for a very short\ni\nLAC\ntime. Without the education of which\nwe have deprived them, how will it\nbe possible tor them to make a living\non the worn-out land that we will\nleave them-? The Progressive Farmer.\nTODAY'S BIRTHDAY HONORS\nCongressman William Patterson\nBorland, of Missouri, was born In\nXeavenworth.'Kans., October 14, 1867;\nwent to Kansas City In 1S80; attended\nward and high schools; graduated\nfrom law department of the University\nof Michigan in 1892; has practiced\nlaw ever since; in 1896 he helped or\nA\nCar ofb\nC. L. Eden\nI\nAnything In the grocery line\nOur stock is fresh and fine!\nButter, and eggs bacon and ham!\nGelatine, jelllcon, Jello and Jam!\nMarmalade, bromangellon, syrup and molasses\nPreserve and Jellies in Jars and glasses.\nNice lemons, oranges, bananas and berries\nPlums, prunes, pears, pineapple and cherries!\nCanteloupes and Melons--crab apples and apple sour and\nand aweet\nGood apples to cook and luscious to eat!\nNice peaches, apricot, grape and nectrlnes;\nAlso rhubarb, asparagus, spinach and green string beans!\nRadishes, carrots, turnips and beets\nAnd every good thing that anyone eats.\nPumpkins, squash, cucumbers and fresh tomatoes!\nCelery, cauliflower, cress and sweet potatoes!\nCanned corn, tomatoes and peas\nPackage-nablsco, festlnos and \"Five o'clock Teas!\"\nCorned beef, sauerkraut and fruit pudlne!\nAnd imported herring and mackerel In brine!\nShrimps, clams and clam chowder!\nSoda, sal soda and baking powder!\nHominy, beans, sago, tapaico and rice!\nHops and sage whole and ground spice.\nSugar granlated, powdered, or bar;\nAlso cocoa and chocolate that comes from afar\nCatsup, sauce and salad dressing!\n(AH our good things will Burely keep you guessing.)\nCandy and honey delicious to eat!\nDates and figs rolled oats and wheat!\nGrape-nuts, corn and maple flakes\nGinger snaps, crackers, cookies and cakes.\nPostum, puffed rice, koffe-et, coffee add tea!\nKorn kinks, force, and egg-o-see!\nCream of wheat, vitos and wheatlne!\nExtracts lemon, vanilla, banana and mapellne;\nNice raisins, currants, citron and lemon peel,\nFlour, gennade and good corn meal,\nSmoked and salted fish and meat;\nAlso vinegar and grape Juice sour and sweet t\nVermacelll, macronl milk and cheese!\n(At Xma time we have Xma trees)\nAnd every good thing to eat\nCranberries, quince and nice mince meat,\nBun, doughnuts, fruit cake and angel food,;\nAlso shredded wheat and celery food.\nFresh yeast, magic yeast and yeast foam.\nThat you use to make bread at home.\nCanned meat, beef extract and cottolene,\nShoe polish, stove blacking and enameline;\nGood lime, brunswlck cleaner and liquid-veneer;\nAlso cider and essence of root beer!\nSalt, starch, soap ajso blueing paddle or ball\nPut up In packages large or small.\nWashing powder, Dutch cleanser and pearline!\nToilet soap castlle and glycerine!\nAmmonia, gold dust and pumice stone!\nBird seed, gravel and cuttle bone!\nBrushes, brooms and mop sticks!\nClothes pins, candles and lamp wicks!\nCrockery, dishes, parafine and sealing wax! v\nJars and glasses-coffee mills and flour sacks!\nAL80 A COMPLETE LINE OF\nDRY GOODS, SHOES, HATS, FEED, IMPLEMENTS\nAND VEHICLES\nHeiisarling\nMercantile\nTUESDAY, OCTOBER H.\nganize the Kansas City school of law;.\nwa elected and served fourteen\nyears; served on the \"Municipal\nLobby\" of Kansas City and has helped\ndraft many laws for the city's man\nagement. He is serving his third\nterm, in Congress.\nYou can flatter a man by calling him\na Bad dog, but call him a measly cur\nand he'll try to alter your map\nf\nPerhaps he Is Just that, Alonzo, but\nwe wouldn't advise you to call the\nmanager of a swimming school a dive\nkeeper.\nPhone 518\na\non\nTrack\nCompany\nK\nr\nI\n1","height":"25912","width":"17320"}}
